               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc>
                     <supportDesc>
                        <support>1 papyrus ; 13.5 x 10.5 cm</support>
                        <condition>
                           <ab type="conservation">The text is on the back of two glued-together, unidentified documents, possibly an official tomos synkollesimos or a private file. It is also possible that unrelated documents were pasted together in order to create a surface to receive the Iliad text. In any case, the documnets were arranged in such a way as to preserve legibility; this argues in favor of a tomos or file but does not rule out the other possibility. One of the documents ca. 8.5 cm wide, contains scattered writing b one hand; the other, ca 2 cm wide, contains 3, possibly 4 hands and may be a register of some kind. The two pieces of papyrus are similar in texture and color, both smooth and light-brown. The Iliad text, which is the beginning of a column is written in dark-brown or black ink.</ab>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout>
                           <ab type="lines">25 lines</ab>
                           <ab type="recto-verso">Source of description: Verso</ab>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <p>Upper margin: 1.5 cm.  The hand reveals large, slightly irregular, and somewhat crowed uncials of 4 mm. in height, and appears to be a typical third centiry A.D. bookhand; P.Berol. 9780r = Seider II 38 (early IIIrd century A.D.). There are numerous stops in evidence, as well three tremata (12, 15, 21) and one breathing mark (13).</p>
                  </handDesc>
               </physDesc>
